## Step 2 ‚Äî detect bootstrap vs rehydrate

Read `.claude/team-forge/{{team}}/tracker/status.json`.

- If missing OR `cohort_count == 0` AND `current_milestone == null` ‚Üí **Bootstrap** (Step 3a)
- Otherwise ‚Üí **Rehydrate** (Step 3b)

## Step 3a ‚Äî bootstrap

1. Read `.claude/team-forge/{{team}}/design.yaml`
2. Read initial brainstorm at `docs/team-forge/{{team}}/brainstorms/<the-one-file>.md`
3. Read initial team-plan at `docs/team-forge/{{team}}/team-plans/<the-one-file>.md` ‚Äî on a
   fresh bootstrap Phase 2 wrote exactly one dated plan (`<slug>-plan-<YYYY-MM-DD>.md`); its
   path is also recorded in `design.yaml` and becomes the tracker's `current_team_plan`. Do
   NOT assume a fixed `team-plan-v1.md` name.
4. Spawn all roster teammates per `design.yaml.rehydrate.respawn_order`. Each spawn prompt carries a
   **scoped brief** ‚Äî you assemble it, the teammate doesn't crawl for it:
   - Role: one of work/verify/advise/tracker/monitor ¬∑ Team: `{{team}}` ¬∑ Project: `{{project_name}}`
   - The teammate's specific task + the exact artifacts it should read (not "go read the KB").
   - **Provider-outage fallback:** if a teammate's model tier is globally unavailable at spawn,
     fall back one tier (e.g. fable ‚Üí opus) rather than failing the launch.
5. Update tracker `status.json`:
   - `current_milestone` ‚Üê first milestone id
   - `current_brainstorm` ‚Üê path to brainstorm
   - `current_team_plan` ‚Üê path to team-plan
   - Append `milestone_started` event
6. Tell user the team is ready; confirm first milestone

## Step 3b ‚Äî rehydrate

Invoke `team-forge:rehydrate` skill. It will:

1. Read tracker/status.json ‚Äî recover team state
2. Read current brainstorm + current team-plan (paths from status.json)
3. Read recent artifacts under `artifacts/<current-milestone>/`
4. Spawn all roster teammates with full context restored
5. Resume coordination from where the prior session left off

> **Staleness check.** This launcher, the agent files, and `gen_dashboard.py` are baked from forge
> time. If the team-forge templates moved since, run `tools/forge.py --check
> .claude/team-forge/{{team}}/design.yaml`; on drift, `--resync` regenerates the template-derived
> files (agents, launcher, renderer) and preserves your tracker state + KB.

## Step 4 ‚Äî coordinate ongoing work

Use as needed:
- `team-forge:brainstorming` ‚Äî develop/revise project understanding
- `team-forge:writing-plans` ‚Äî plan/replan delegation

For domain work, reference the team's discovered skills (see design.yaml's `skill_discovery_results`).

Manage the shared task list via the `Task*` tools (`TaskCreate`/`TaskList`/`TaskUpdate`) ‚Äî it's native to your session's team, not a hand-managed path. Dispatch via `SendMessage`. Arbitrate verdicts.

**Drive milestones to their gate, don't idle for input.** Within a milestone, keep the work moving
continuously ‚Äî never report-and-wait for a "keep going" between tasks. Pause **only** at a milestone's
declared human go/no-go (`next_phase_check`): don't auto-advance *past* it, but don't stop *before*
reaching it either. Being invoked means the user wants the milestone driven to completion.

**Per-agent memory is native, not yours to curate.** The **advise** role (dispatched on-demand) has its
own persistent agent memory ‚Äî Claude Code auto-injects and lets it self-manage `.claude/agent-memory/{{team}}-<name>/`.
Standing **work/verify** teammates get **no** per-agent memory (Claude Code ignores `memory:` on the
teammate path), so their durable context is *this KB + the shared task list* ‚Äî keep those current and
hand a good scoped brief on each (re)spawn. You do not harvest anyone's memory.

## Memory authority

You are the single-writer for `docs/team-forge/{{team}}/{brainstorms,team-plans,artifacts,runtime}/`.
A dispatched teammate with native `memory:` (e.g. advise) curates its **own** `.claude/agent-memory/‚Ä¶`
directory ‚Äî that is not yours and you do not write it.
{{LEDGER_OWNERSHIP_BLOCK}}

## Naming discipline (IDs stay internal)

Milestone IDs (`m1`, `phase-b`) are **internal-ledger-only** (status.json + design.yaml). Outward
surfaces use the milestone's human-readable NAME: commit messages, PR titles, code comments, and KB
doc filenames/headers. Narrative artifacts get content-descriptive names that carry a **date marker** ‚Äî
`<subject>-<artifact-kind>-<YYYY-MM-DD>.md` (`verification-walkthrough-2026-07-02.md`,
`migration-plan-2026-07-02.md`), never a generic/undated `design-3.md`; a team accumulates several such
docs over its life, so the date keeps them distinguishable and orderable. Artifact directories are
descriptive slugs, never `artifacts/m1/`. **Fixed-name machine contracts are exempt** (`design.yaml`,
`status.json`, `manifest.json`, `dashboard.html`, KB `README.md`) ‚Äî they are read by fixed name and there
is exactly one. If an ID must appear on a durable surface, carry a glossary.

